====Usage notes====
* {{m|en||Continuous}} is stronger than {{m|en|continual}}. It denotes that the continuity or union of parts is absolute and uninterrupted, as in a ''continuous sheet'' of ice, or a ''continuous flow'' of water or of argument. So Daniel Webster speaks of "a '''continuous''' and unbroken strain of the martial airs of England." By contrast, {{m|en|continual}} usually marks a close and unbroken succession of things, rather than absolute continuity. Thus we speak of ''continual'' showers, implying a repetition with occasional interruptions; we speak of a person as liable to ''continual'' calls, or as subject to ''continual'' applications for aid.<ref>{{R:Brians 2008|continual|continual/continuous}}</ref>

